1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:17,922
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:19,910 --> 00:00:32,128
Satsang with Mooji Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:33,810 --> 00:00:37,655
Okay, well I've entitled this, No More Ideology.

4
00:00:38,996 --> 00:00:42,862
So he's always going to be about that.

5
00:00:42,883 --> 00:00:47,149
So just looking back at this past century,

6
00:00:48,901 --> 00:00:51,784
we've had these three secular ideologies.

7
00:00:53,267 --> 00:00:59,975
And these really, the idea of ideologies really began when writing began.

8
00:01:00,637 --> 00:01:06,846
And of course, for something like 2,000 years or less than that, it was a Christian ideology.

9
00:01:07,566 --> 00:01:16,900
So what we mean by that is that there is some sort of vision in the future to which you're heading, whether it be the promised land,

10
00:01:16,879 --> 00:01:45,924
or you know the final days or whether it be the wonderful communist state etc so here this last century we've had these three so communism posited this the idea that the ordinary person should be the focus of all state activity it should be the commune it should be the society and

11
00:01:46,090 --> 00:01:52,882
As we know from Animal Farm, even though everybody was equal, some became more equal than others.

12
00:01:52,921 --> 00:02:05,064
And of course, if you are, if you have an idea of where you want to go, some sort of vision, you've got to force people there.

13
00:02:05,686 --> 00:02:08,570
So you naturally move towards authoritarianism.

14
00:02:10,627 --> 00:02:15,955
Then the next one, which came sort of after that, was National Socialism.

15
00:02:16,937 --> 00:02:28,516
And if the communism arose as a response, not to industrial society, remember, but to pre-industrial society, the terrible sufferings of the Russian peasants.

16
00:02:28,936 --> 00:02:32,562
The National Socialism.

17
00:02:33,044 --> 00:02:34,145
Come in, Gwen.

18
00:02:34,407 --> 00:02:35,068
Very welcome.

19
00:02:35,187 --> 00:02:37,453
Do you want a chair or a cushion?

20
00:02:39,978 --> 00:02:41,600
You've missed the amazing opening lines.

21
00:02:42,521 --> 00:02:49,475
Yeah, you'll have to catch up, I'm afraid.

22
00:02:49,455 --> 00:03:06,063
National socialism, especially in Germany, was a response to the really atrocious retributions that were demanded after the First World War, which drove the Germans to real absolute poverty.

23
00:03:06,819 --> 00:03:14,487
And there, of course, like all nationalisms, the nation is the focus.

24
00:03:15,468 --> 00:03:18,393
And you have an ideal as to what your nation is.

25
00:03:18,432 --> 00:03:26,981
And of course, when it's wrapped up with racial ideology, then you've got a real hard mix.

26
00:03:27,002 --> 00:03:29,324
And that's what happened, as you know, in Germany.

27
00:03:29,724 --> 00:03:31,426
It wasn't so much in Italy.

28
00:03:33,044 --> 00:03:34,025
or indeed in Spain.

29
00:03:34,346 --> 00:03:39,391
But again, once you have a vision, you've got to force everybody to get there.

30
00:03:39,913 --> 00:03:42,956
And anybody who gets in the way, you basically, well, you get rid of.

31
00:03:45,520 --> 00:03:47,081
So that was the second one.

32
00:03:47,141 --> 00:03:51,347
So the first one was dependent on the people, the commune.

33
00:03:51,948 --> 00:03:54,411
The second one was on the nation.

34
00:03:54,457 --> 00:04:00,144
And now the third one is dependent on the sovereign self.

35
00:04:00,843 --> 00:04:02,105
And that's neoliberalism.

36
00:04:03,127 --> 00:04:06,270
And it came in very, very sneakily.

37
00:04:06,389 --> 00:04:09,592
It came in as an economic program.

38
00:04:10,394 --> 00:04:12,235
It didn't come in as an ideology.

39
00:04:13,016 --> 00:04:20,043
But in fact, at the base of it, there was definitely the understanding that the primary person was the entrepreneur.

40
00:04:20,598 --> 00:04:31,291
And the whole of society should make the market, the free market, their basic platform for the entrepreneur.

41
00:04:31,932 --> 00:04:36,077
And the entrepreneur was, everybody had to be within the market.

42
00:04:36,197 --> 00:04:38,600
If you're not in the market, then you're useless.

43
00:04:38,661 --> 00:04:41,404
You're not part of that process.

44
00:04:42,646 --> 00:04:49,035
And so anybody who made lots of money, like these billionaires, were the heroes.

45
00:04:49,201 --> 00:04:52,646
And the whole idea, of course, is that the money would trickle down.

46
00:04:53,047 --> 00:04:56,012
Well, it has, but it really is a trickle.

47
00:04:56,552 --> 00:04:58,817
And it's all swamped upwards.

48
00:04:59,637 --> 00:05:10,095
So this idea of having some sort of aim, some sort of ideal, the free market at all costs, no matter what,

49
00:05:11,154 --> 00:05:14,480
And then the ideal of this wonderful individual.

50
00:05:15,021 --> 00:05:26,197
So, you know, just to quote Margaret Thatcher, for which she's very famous, you can see the shift, right?

51
00:05:26,257 --> 00:05:28,540
So away from communism, okay?

52
00:05:29,221 --> 00:05:38,817
I think we've gone through a period when too many children and people have been given to understand, I have a problem, it is the government's job to cope with it.

53
00:05:39,168 --> 00:05:42,672
Or I have a problem, I will go and get a grant to cope with it.

54
00:05:43,333 --> 00:05:45,776
I'm homeless, the government must house me.

55
00:05:47,077 --> 00:05:50,442
And so they are casting their problems on society.

56
00:05:50,641 --> 00:05:51,983
And who is society?

57
00:05:52,004 --> 00:05:53,365
So this is the classic one, isn't it?

58
00:05:53,805 --> 00:05:54,846
There is no such thing.

59
00:05:54,867 --> 00:05:58,451
There are only individual men and women and their families.

60
00:05:58,951 --> 00:06:00,112
Note that, families, yeah?

61
00:06:00,673 --> 00:06:06,440
And no government can do anything except through people and people look to themselves first.

62
00:06:07,670 --> 00:06:08,572
So that's a reaction.

63
00:06:08,932 --> 00:06:20,654
But what, of course, is missing out in that equation, which is strange for a scientist, she had a chemistry degree, is that the whole is always greater than the part, the number of the parts.

64
00:06:21,055 --> 00:06:26,125
So if you've got oxygen and hydrogen, well, they're completely separate.

65
00:06:26,165 --> 00:06:29,172
Put them together and you've got this magical substance.

66
00:06:29,151 --> 00:06:33,399
So, of course, when people get together, what you form is community.

67
00:06:34,262 --> 00:06:41,615
And we know from the way that she behaved, she was quite happy to destroy communities in order to get her aim.

68
00:06:42,377 --> 00:06:46,625
But it wasn't so much her specifically.

69
00:06:46,845 --> 00:06:51,192
This was the ideology that the neoliberals brought in.

70
00:06:51,173 --> 00:06:57,884
And if you really want to see how bad it was, I don't know whether you've ever come across the shock doctrine by Naomi Klein.

71
00:06:58,245 --> 00:07:02,892
If you've read that, then you'll see what a horror story it is for places like Chile.

72
00:07:03,553 --> 00:07:10,886
And of course, it was tremendously humiliating for Russia, you know, when they gave up, especially with the Americans going around saying, we won.

73
00:07:13,069 --> 00:07:15,915
I mean, that was really crass.

74
00:07:15,894 --> 00:07:28,627
So this is individuals seeking their own self-interest benefit for the economy as a whole.

75
00:07:28,968 --> 00:07:40,098
Now, that actually goes back to Smith, where he's trying to explain what the so-called hidden hand of the markets are.

76
00:07:40,538 --> 00:07:44,382
Now, even though you're working for yourself, you're actually creating benefit for others.

77
00:07:45,442 --> 00:07:52,350
Now, what I was particularly interested in was this idea of a sovereign self.

78
00:07:52,411 --> 00:07:55,494
So I do my own thing in my own time, in my own way.

79
00:07:55,894 --> 00:07:58,096
And you'll all remember Frank Sinatra.

80
00:07:58,117 --> 00:07:59,098
I did it my way.

81
00:08:00,319 --> 00:08:08,007
So the West has really developed, especially in America and Britain, this idea of the solitary person.

82
00:08:07,987 --> 00:08:12,184
who makes things happen without anybody else, really.

83
00:08:12,605 --> 00:08:16,862
I mean, the fact that they become billionaires on the backs of everybody is immaterial.

84
00:08:16,961 --> 00:08:18,065
They did it, you know.

85
00:08:19,041 --> 00:08:20,043
So it's the same here.

86
00:08:20,843 --> 00:08:26,750
Occasionally people say to me, you know, you've done an amazing job, you know, what a vision.

87
00:08:27,571 --> 00:08:30,875
But there's nothing specifically wonderful about this vision.

88
00:08:31,415 --> 00:08:39,624
Anybody who's been to something like 15 meditation centers like I have knows what a meditation center is supposed to look like.

89
00:08:40,544 --> 00:08:44,509
And of course, the reason why this has happened as it is, is because

90
00:08:44,842 --> 00:08:47,894
When we bought the place, it was already set.

91
00:08:47,933 --> 00:08:55,883
There was already a bungalow there and there was already an annex which ended here where that wall is, you see.

92
00:08:56,452 --> 00:08:59,255
So it was only working with that and then asking people.

93
00:08:59,716 --> 00:09:01,158
It was people's ideas, really.

94
00:09:01,177 --> 00:09:03,760
It wasn't my idea to have a decking, for instance.

95
00:09:04,160 --> 00:09:06,803
That was somebody else said that, you know.

96
00:09:06,823 --> 00:09:15,552
And the fact that we ended up with an accommodation block, again, was people sort of moaning about sharing rooms.

97
00:09:18,176 --> 00:09:22,139
And so everything sort of happened as it were, gently.

98
00:09:22,677 --> 00:09:28,014
The only thing I take perhaps a little bit of credit for is the stupor.

99
00:09:28,355 --> 00:09:35,320
That was my ideological statement, the stupor.

100
00:09:35,806 --> 00:09:44,236
Okay, anyway, there was a wonderful article taken from The Survival of the Richest by Douglas Rushkoff.

101
00:09:44,256 --> 00:09:51,285
It was, and I picked this up and it said, I have to read it.

102
00:09:51,427 --> 00:09:56,273
It's not particularly that long, but it's a good piece of literature.

103
00:09:56,312 --> 00:09:59,417
So he says, so Douglas Rushkoff, okay.

104
00:09:59,397 --> 00:10:06,942
As a humanist who writes about the impact of digital technology on our lives, I'm often mistaken for a futurist.

105
00:10:07,159 --> 00:10:23,799
The people most interested in hiring my opinions about technology are usually less concerned with the building tools that help people live better lives in the present than they are in identifying the next big thing through which to dominate them in the future.

106
00:10:24,561 --> 00:10:27,144
I don't usually respond to their inquiries.

107
00:10:27,604 --> 00:10:32,370
Why help these guys ruin what's left of the internet, much less civilization?

108
00:10:33,471 --> 00:10:34,972
See where he's coming from.

109
00:10:34,952 --> 00:10:52,932
Still, sometimes a combination of morbid curiosity and cold hard cash is enough to get me on a stage in front of the tech elite, where I try to talk some sense into them about how their businesses are affecting our lives, out here in the real world.

110
00:10:53,734 --> 00:11:04,385
That's how I found myself accepting an invitation to address a group mysteriously described as ultra-wealthy stakeholders,

111
00:11:04,365 --> 00:11:06,168
out in the middle of the desert.

112
00:11:08,149 --> 00:11:15,437
A limo was waiting for me at the airport, and as the sun began to dip over the horizon, I realized I'd been in the car for three hours.

113
00:11:16,359 --> 00:11:21,384
What sort of wealthy hedge fund types would drive this far from the airport for a conference?

114
00:11:22,105 --> 00:11:32,196
Then I saw it, on a parallel path next to a highway, as if racing against us, a small jet was coming in for landing on a private airfield, of course.

115
00:11:32,969 --> 00:11:42,999
The next morning, two men in matching Patagonia fleeces came for me in a golf cart and conveyed me through rocks and underbrush to a meeting hall.

116
00:11:44,220 --> 00:11:49,104
They left me to drink coffee and prepare in what I figured was serving as my green room.

117
00:11:49,705 --> 00:11:56,892
But instead of me being wired with a microphone or taking to a stage, my audience was brought in to me.

118
00:11:56,951 --> 00:12:01,355
They sat around the table and introduced themselves.

119
00:12:01,336 --> 00:12:08,668
Five super wealthy guys, yes, all men, from the upper echelon of the tech investing and hedge fund world.

120
00:12:09,429 --> 00:12:11,133
At least two of them were billionaires.

121
00:12:12,054 --> 00:12:19,226
And after a bit of small talk, I realized they had no interest in the speech I had prepared about the future of technology.

122
00:12:19,206 --> 00:12:21,009
They had come to ask questions.

123
00:12:22,130 --> 00:12:34,990
They started out innocuously and predictably enough, Bitcoin or Ethereum, virtual reality or augmented reality, who will get quantum computing first, China or Google.

124
00:12:35,750 --> 00:12:41,278
Eventually, they edged into their real topic of concern, New Zealand or Alaska.

125
00:12:42,760 --> 00:12:46,767
Which region would be less affected by the coming climate crisis?

126
00:12:48,096 --> 00:12:49,479
It only got worse from there.

127
00:12:50,139 --> 00:12:54,086
Which was the greater threat, global warming or biological warfare?

128
00:12:54,967 --> 00:13:00,136
How long should one plan to be able to survive with no outside help?

129
00:13:01,219 --> 00:13:03,643
Should a shelter have its own air supply?

130
00:13:04,543 --> 00:13:08,129
What was the likelihood of groundwater contamination?

131
00:13:08,481 --> 00:13:24,582
Finally, the CEO of a brokerage house explained that he had nearly completed building his own underground bunker system and asked, ''How do I maintain authority over my security force after the event?''

132
00:13:24,918 --> 00:13:29,625
The event, that was their euphemism for environmental collapse.

133
00:13:30,605 --> 00:13:39,460
Social unrest, nuclear explosion, solar storm, unstoppable virus or malicious computer hack that takes everything down.

134
00:13:40,881 --> 00:13:44,326
This single question occupied us for the rest of the hour.

135
00:13:45,288 --> 00:13:52,578
They knew armed guards would be required to protect their compounds from raiders as well as angry mobs.

136
00:13:52,897 --> 00:14:00,366
One had already secured a dozen Navy SEALs to make their way to his compound if he gave them the right cue.

137
00:14:00,407 --> 00:14:06,936
But how would he pay the guards once even his crypto was worthless?

138
00:14:07,836 --> 00:14:12,663
What would stop the guards from eventually choosing their own leader?

139
00:14:12,683 --> 00:14:19,393
The billionaires considered using special combination locks on the food supply that only they knew.

140
00:14:21,955 --> 00:14:22,836
It's crazy, isn't it?

141
00:14:24,119 --> 00:14:29,386
Or making guards wear disciplinary collars of some kind in return for their survival.

142
00:14:31,149 --> 00:14:37,660
Or maybe building robots to serve as guards and workers if that technology could be developed in time.

143
00:14:37,701 --> 00:14:44,351
It's as if they want to build a car that goes fast enough to escape its own exhaust.

144
00:14:45,900 --> 00:14:47,683
I tried to reason with them.

145
00:14:47,703 --> 00:14:54,794
I made pro-social arguments for partnership and solidarity as the best approaches to our collective long-term challenges.

146
00:14:55,615 --> 00:15:01,846
The way to get your guards to exhibit loyalty in the future was to treat them like friends right now, I explained.

147
00:15:02,486 --> 00:15:05,250
Don't just invest in ammo and electric fences.

148
00:15:05,631 --> 00:15:07,715
Invest in people and relationships.

149
00:15:08,395 --> 00:15:12,802
They rolled their eyes at what must have sounded to them like hippie philosophy.

150
00:15:14,317 --> 00:15:18,745
This was probably the wealthiest, most powerful group I'd ever encountered.

151
00:15:19,265 --> 00:15:28,842
Yet here they were, asking a Marxist media theorist for advice on where and how to configure their doomsday bunkers.

152
00:15:28,863 --> 00:15:30,666
That's when it hit me.

153
00:15:31,126 --> 00:15:37,778
At least as far as these gentlemen were concerned, this was a talk about the future of technology.

154
00:15:38,821 --> 00:16:01,032
Taking their cue from Tesla founder Elon Musk colonizing Mars and Palantir's Peter Thiel reversing the aging process or artificial intelligence developers Sam Altman and Ray Kurzweil uploading their minds into supercomputers.

155
00:16:01,011 --> 00:16:11,565
They were preparing for a digital future that had less to do with making the world a better place than it did with transcending the human condition altogether.

156
00:16:12,466 --> 00:16:27,524
Their extreme wealth and privilege served only to make them obsessed with insulating themselves from the very real and present danger of climate change, rising sea levels, mass migrations, global epidemics,

157
00:16:28,179 --> 00:16:32,707
global pandemics, nativist panic and resource depletion.

158
00:16:33,148 --> 00:16:41,743
For them, the future of technology is about only one thing, escape from the rest of us.

159
00:16:41,763 --> 00:16:42,604
It's stunning, isn't it?

160
00:16:43,125 --> 00:16:45,528
Stunning, absolutely stunning.

161
00:16:45,548 --> 00:16:47,753
So that's where we're at.

162
00:16:48,312 --> 00:16:53,461
That's the end game of neoliberalism, the sovereign self.

163
00:16:54,741 --> 00:17:13,097
So what we have, of course, still just about in this country, I think, is a liberal democracy, which is trying to hold, isn't it, the balance between social demands and personal needs and allowing that sort of individual liberty within the constraints of a community.

164
00:17:14,661 --> 00:17:16,884
But as you know, when it comes under pressure,

165
00:17:17,606 --> 00:17:20,250
then you have these two wings come up.

166
00:17:21,251 --> 00:17:23,335
So where can you go now?

167
00:17:23,494 --> 00:17:24,938
What's the next ideology?

168
00:17:25,137 --> 00:17:31,948
We've done the community bit with communism, we've done the nation bit, and we've done the sovereign self.

169
00:17:32,508 --> 00:17:34,991
So there's nowhere else to go, is there?

170
00:17:35,393 --> 00:17:36,433
So you've got to go back.

171
00:17:36,513 --> 00:17:44,542
You've got to either become a communist or a national socialist or keep banging on about being a sovereign self.

172
00:17:45,243 --> 00:17:53,292
We seem to be locked in now in a sort of ideological cul-de-sac.

173
00:17:54,034 --> 00:18:01,823
Can you think of any other ideology that you can hang, any other basis that you can hang an ideology on?

174
00:18:03,135 --> 00:18:10,865
So an ideology, remember, is some futuristic aim that you're going towards and you just make for it.

175
00:18:11,366 --> 00:18:15,613
There's a lovely little tale I heard about.

176
00:18:15,992 --> 00:18:18,957
They had a big communist conference in Moscow.

177
00:18:19,577 --> 00:18:25,506
And it was a French writer, but I just can't recall the name.

178
00:18:25,586 --> 00:18:28,911
But they were talking about the perfect communist state.

179
00:18:29,090 --> 00:18:32,855
What would constitute the perfect communist state?

180
00:18:32,886 --> 00:18:36,852
And he asked, what about accidents?

181
00:18:38,272 --> 00:18:41,416
And seemingly there was a silence.

182
00:18:41,436 --> 00:18:45,221
And then a voice came out from the darkness.

183
00:18:46,082 --> 00:18:51,828
In a communist state, there will be no accidents.

184
00:18:51,848 --> 00:18:55,853
That would be brilliant.

185
00:18:55,873 --> 00:19:00,919
So, and of course the question is...

186
00:19:03,498 --> 00:19:04,740
What can Buddhism offer?

187
00:19:04,759 --> 00:19:05,681
What, you know, like that.

188
00:19:06,582 --> 00:19:08,763
By the way, I have got here, I love quoting this.

189
00:19:08,984 --> 00:19:11,907
I just, I mean, you see it quoted all over the place now.

190
00:19:11,948 --> 00:19:13,289
The second coming by Yeats.

191
00:19:14,250 --> 00:19:19,176
Turning and turning in the widening Gaia, the falcon cannot hear the falcon.

192
00:19:19,196 --> 00:19:20,057
That's wonderful, isn't it?

193
00:19:20,097 --> 00:19:24,042
The rich can't hear the poor, you know, the powerful can't hear that.

194
00:19:24,063 --> 00:19:29,690
And we sort of separate, you know, immigrants or natives can't hear the immigrants and so on and so forth.

195
00:19:29,710 --> 00:19:32,053
Things fall apart, the center cannot hold.

196
00:19:32,272 --> 00:19:32,913
It's great, isn't it?

197
00:19:33,738 --> 00:19:35,700
Mere anarchy is loosed upon the world.

198
00:19:37,781 --> 00:19:43,808
You might have come across Jem Bendell and others trying to work on catastrophe studies.

199
00:19:44,490 --> 00:19:50,876
I think there's actually university departments now, isn't that right, Gwen?

200
00:19:50,896 --> 00:19:51,698
Collapsology.

201
00:19:51,958 --> 00:19:53,200
Collapsology, that's it.

202
00:19:53,220 --> 00:19:54,181
Collapsologists.

203
00:19:54,201 --> 00:19:56,363
Collapsologists.

204
00:19:56,383 --> 00:19:58,025
There is an actual discipline now.

205
00:19:58,705 --> 00:19:59,846
That's how bad it gets.

206
00:20:00,686 --> 00:20:04,771
The blood-din tide is loosed and everywhere the ceremony of innocence is drowned.

207
00:20:04,932 --> 00:20:09,817
The best lack all conviction, whilst the worst are full of passionate intensity.

208
00:20:10,417 --> 00:20:11,558
And you can see that, can't you?

209
00:20:11,578 --> 00:20:16,325
You can see that the liberal establishment is sort of confused.

210
00:20:16,345 --> 00:20:19,248
It doesn't know what to do about mass immigration.

211
00:20:19,268 --> 00:20:21,490
It doesn't know what to do about the Kleist.

212
00:20:21,631 --> 00:20:28,077
It doesn't have a clear direction, which it would have had, say, after the Second World War.

213
00:20:29,559 --> 00:20:32,051
So somehow we have to transcend this.

214
00:20:32,473 --> 00:20:38,102
And if we go back to the time of the Buddha, there are no ideologies.

215
00:20:38,217 --> 00:20:40,980
You know, because writing, nobody was writing.

216
00:20:41,361 --> 00:20:42,481
There wasn't anything written.

217
00:20:42,521 --> 00:20:44,545
He was illiterate.

218
00:20:45,425 --> 00:20:49,111
And so there wasn't the opportunity to think about thinking.

219
00:20:49,431 --> 00:20:50,992
So there's no systems theory.

220
00:20:51,432 --> 00:20:53,576
There's nothing like that at all.

221
00:20:53,675 --> 00:21:00,765
What there is are customs, laws and customs that have been worked out through ages and ages and ages.

222
00:21:00,913 --> 00:21:26,449
and moral reasoning so if you look at um you know hinduism or jainism or buddhism it's all about the psychology of moral behavior and their language is that so whereas we would talk about the purification of the heart these days it's medicalized it's a therapy to get to get over your internal problem and uh

223
00:21:28,453 --> 00:21:32,338
And we're going to read this at the stupa there.

224
00:21:32,799 --> 00:21:38,407
So if you now put aside any idea that we're going anywhere, right?

225
00:21:38,748 --> 00:21:41,291
So there's no such thing as a perfect society.

226
00:21:41,652 --> 00:21:46,659
There's no such thing as moving towards some sort of future Shangri-La.

227
00:21:46,919 --> 00:21:49,482
It's always going to be like this, right?

228
00:21:49,462 --> 00:21:54,931
There's always going to be misery, suffering, spiced with an occasional bit of joy.

229
00:21:57,674 --> 00:21:59,156
This is what we call samsara.

230
00:22:00,459 --> 00:22:04,925
But we do have an aim, but the aim is completely beyond the phenomenal world.

231
00:22:05,006 --> 00:22:07,048
It's beyond anything that you can imagine.

232
00:22:07,368 --> 00:22:13,377
It's beyond anything that you can create with your mind as a beautiful and wonderful society.

233
00:22:13,544 --> 00:22:28,515
But of course, the fundamental error or delusion that we suffer from is to believe that we are human beings and therefore we do seek happiness in this form, in this world.

234
00:22:29,390 --> 00:22:35,455
And it's because of that that we create all this business about selfishness, which is translated as the sovereign self.

235
00:22:36,016 --> 00:22:37,156
You know, greed is good.

236
00:22:37,397 --> 00:22:38,538
Yeah.

237
00:22:39,118 --> 00:22:41,141
And of course, that creates problems for us.

238
00:22:41,280 --> 00:22:44,344
So we push away, we get rid of anything that we don't like.

239
00:22:44,423 --> 00:22:45,345
So you get the aversion.

240
00:22:45,726 --> 00:22:47,007
If it's too big, you run for it.

241
00:22:47,406 --> 00:22:55,734
So there's your basic fundamental attitudes that arise from that delusion, acquisitiveness, aversion and fear.

242
00:22:55,714 --> 00:23:04,387
And from there, all our actions sort of spread outwards and create a second tier of horror, of shame, guilt, remorse and all the rest of it.

243
00:23:06,090 --> 00:23:24,979
So if we start from a basis of no ideology, in other words, we're not going anywhere to some great, amazing place and instead draw ourselves, like the Buddha would have done, down to his present day situation,

244
00:23:25,178 --> 00:23:26,842
And obviously it wasn't perfect.

245
00:23:26,862 --> 00:23:39,910
For instance, you know, there's lots of talk in the scriptures about these useless, massive sacrifices that were made on the understanding that the gods would respond so long as the sacrifice was done perfectly.

246
00:23:40,451 --> 00:23:45,162
So this had moved away from the time when they were petitions to gods.

247
00:23:45,142 --> 00:24:13,410
where the gods might or might not reply but it came to a point by the time that the buddhas was alive that if you did the sacrifice perfectly we talk about hundreds of cattle hundreds of horses the king's sacrifice then the gods had to sort of reply and of course it probably wasn't working just like in Socrates time people were losing faith in the gods you know

248
00:24:15,634 --> 00:24:20,983
And so it's not as though everything is right at the Buddha's time.

249
00:24:21,605 --> 00:24:23,208
I mean, obviously not.

250
00:24:23,608 --> 00:24:27,316
And there were kings who were creating war and all sorts of messing about.

251
00:24:27,796 --> 00:24:29,378
And there was ordinary crime, etc.

252
00:24:29,839 --> 00:24:34,407
But there was no sort of, as I say, this Shangri-La.

253
00:24:34,468 --> 00:24:38,976
So all the teaching of these religions, of these religions,

254
00:24:38,955 --> 00:24:47,230
These dispensations were always drawn towards the society as it is now and how you could make it better.

255
00:24:48,030 --> 00:24:57,707
And so when it came to the Buddha's own thing, he has quite a bit of advice on what keeps a society together as a community.

256
00:24:58,176 --> 00:25:00,325
And so this is it here.

257
00:25:00,365 --> 00:25:06,548
See, at the time when the venerable Ananda was standing behind fanning him, the Blessed One addressed him.

258
00:25:06,588 --> 00:25:09,621
This had happened because

259
00:25:10,866 --> 00:25:25,213
the son of Bimbisara, whose name just escapes me now, had sent a diplomat or one of his ambassadors to see the Buddha to ask whether this was a good time to attack the bhajis.

260
00:25:25,394 --> 00:25:29,060
I mean, what an interesting question to ask the Buddha.

261
00:25:29,741 --> 00:25:31,625
Is this a good time to attack them?

262
00:25:31,605 --> 00:25:37,416
Well, he didn't actually answer directly, but he gave these sort of things to consider.

263
00:25:37,778 --> 00:25:41,484
And he asks, he asks, so he's asking Ananda, you see.

264
00:25:41,505 --> 00:25:50,761
He says, have you heard, Ananda, that the Vajji Confederacy has frequent gatherings and their meetings are well attended?

265
00:25:50,741 --> 00:25:53,685
And there's a refrain after each of these questions.

266
00:25:54,366 --> 00:25:56,229
I have heard, Lord, that this is so.

267
00:25:56,730 --> 00:26:03,858
So long, Ananda, as this is the case, the growth of the Vajis is to be expected, not their decline.

268
00:26:05,240 --> 00:26:06,000
And then he goes on.

269
00:26:06,221 --> 00:26:13,611
Do the Vajis assemble and disperse peacefully and attend to their affairs in concord?

270
00:26:15,193 --> 00:26:17,256
you know, considering our politics.

271
00:26:18,237 --> 00:26:26,365
Do the Vajis neither enact new degrees nor abolish existing ones, but proceed in accordance with ancient constitutions?

272
00:26:26,925 --> 00:26:32,912
That sounds very conservative, small c, but that would be the basis where you start from.

273
00:26:32,932 --> 00:26:36,234
You accept those and then presumably you'd move from them.

274
00:26:37,915 --> 00:26:44,542
Do the Vajis show respect, honour, esteem and veneration towards elders and think it worthwhile to listen to them?

275
00:26:46,682 --> 00:26:54,878
Have you heard, Ananda, do the Vajis refrain from abducting women and maidens of good families and from detaining them?

276
00:26:55,319 --> 00:27:03,234
So this, of course, you could extend to all the prejudices of, you know, sexual, race, racial, and I may as well plug ageism here.

277
00:27:03,836 --> 00:27:06,582
Well, that's it.

278
00:27:07,490 --> 00:27:30,797
do they show respect honor and esteem and veneration towards their shrines both of those in the city and outside and do not deprive them of due offerings as given and made by them formally so this of course is pointing to freedom of belief freedom of speech and so on and then finally duly protect and guard the other house so that so that they can come to the realm

279
00:27:30,777 --> 00:27:33,484
and live there in peace.

280
00:27:33,545 --> 00:27:38,178
So this is really respecting both religious and civic leaders.

281
00:27:38,720 --> 00:27:45,900
If all these are followed then according to the Buddha then you can expect growth and not decline.

282
00:27:47,432 --> 00:27:53,022
So, I mean, you have to always translate this stuff, of course, into our present day.

283
00:27:53,984 --> 00:28:02,421
But you can see that he's very much about community, about people talking to each other and discussing things, coming to agreements.

284
00:28:03,920 --> 00:28:14,877
And then a passage here where he talks about six things that foster love and respect, helpfulness and agreement, harmony and unity.

285
00:28:15,519 --> 00:28:19,384
So again, this is, you know, just basic ethics.

286
00:28:19,484 --> 00:28:25,454
So he's talking to monks now, but you can translate it, obviously.

287
00:28:25,434 --> 00:28:54,075
when one acts with love towards one's companions in the spiritual life, both in public and in private, when one speaks with love towards them, both in public and in private, and when one thinks with love towards them, both in public and in private, when one shares with them, without reservation, whatever one has acquired justly, even if it be no more than the food in one's alms bowl,

288
00:28:54,055 --> 00:29:17,515
when one possesses together with them virtues that are complete unbroken and freedom giving praised by the wise and conducive to concentration and when one possesses with one's companions in the holy life both in public and in private the understanding that is noble leading to freedom and which conduces to the complete destruction of suffering

289
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:23,471
Then will there be love and respect, helpfulness and agreement, harmony and unity.

290
00:29:24,153 --> 00:29:28,983
So again, you have to translate this into ordinary daily life.

291
00:29:29,324 --> 00:29:35,537
But you can see the directions are always about ethics, about moral behavior.

292
00:29:36,901 --> 00:29:54,910
And then finally, there's a lovely passage where he meets some Arahats, I think three of them living together, and he asks them, how do they live in harmony, mutual appreciation and agreeability, like milk and water mixed, regarding each other with kindly eyes?

293
00:29:55,597 --> 00:30:04,627
And one of them, Anna Ruda, replied, I always consider what a blessing it is, what a real blessing, that I'm living with such companions in the spiritual life.

294
00:30:05,449 --> 00:30:09,614
I think, speak and act with love towards them, both in public and in private.

295
00:30:10,255 --> 00:30:16,902
I always consider that I should put aside my own wishes and acquiesce to what they want, and then I do that.

296
00:30:17,522 --> 00:30:21,807
Thus, we are many in body, but one in heart, one at heart.

297
00:30:22,919 --> 00:30:46,945
So here we have both an idea of what the Buddha, an approach, what we're interested in is not exactly what he says, but his approach to community, which is to establish that sense of togetherness and the whole business of sharing and of kindly love, etc., etc.

298
00:30:48,748 --> 00:30:51,711
So I think...

299
00:30:53,125 --> 00:31:22,153
I think if we could just for one minute abandon all ideologies and just come down to a basic grounded moral and ethical reasoning, you know, with a present day aim of creating a consistent state of community with everything that word means, you know, that is my hope.

300
00:31:23,163 --> 00:31:40,834
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that I have not caused even greater confusion or argument, and that you will, by your devotion to practice, liberate yourself and help others liberate themselves sooner rather than later.

